<manpage>
    <sample url="datatypes\ezstr\wchar_t">operator wchar_t*</sample>
    <volume> Common data structure </volume>
    <interface> EzStr </interface>
    <method> operator datatypes </method>

    <description>
        <para> The type conversion operator. Currently the converted type, which Elastos supports include: transform an EzStr string to a wchar_t* string.</para>
    </description>

    <syntax>
        <method_name> operator const wchar_t* </method_name>
        <NoArguments/>
   </syntax>
    <syntax>
        <method_name> operator wchar_t* </method_name>
   </syntax>

    <return>
        <para>Returns the necessary data type, which is transformed from EzStr variable. The content of the data is not changed.</para>
    </return>

    <remarks>
        <para>After transforming an EzStr type to a double byte width wchar_t* type, we can access the memory pointed by the wchar_t* pointer directly. It is more efficient this way. One must pay attention to the size of the buffer when storing data in the buffer. Although the data in the buffer may be changed through the pointer and if the effective length of the data is changed, one must set the '\0' at the end of the string manually. It has limitations too. One cannot change the effective data length, which is stored inside EzStr. In other words, one gets the original value by invoking Length.</para>
    </remarks>

    <example><pre><![CDATA[
#include <stdio.h>
#include <ezstr.h>

int __cdecl main()
{
    EzStr str1 = EZCSTR("Hello,world!");

    wchar_t* wstr1 = (wchar_t*)str1;
    wprintf(L"This ezstr is: %s\n", wstr1);

    return 0;
}
]]></pre></example>

    <result>
    <![CDATA[
This ezstr is: Hello,world!
]]>
    </result>

</manpage>